<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Quick tour of HDclustVS</h1>
<h4 class="author">Beomseok Seo</h4>
<h4 class="date">2021-04-22</h4>



<div id="introduction" class="section level2">
<h2>1. Introduction</h2>
<p><samp>HDclustVS</samp> is an R package for new block-wise variable selection methods for clustering, <samp>HMM-VB-VS</samp> and <samp>GMM-VB-VS</samp>, which exploit the latent states of the hidden Markov model on variable blocks or Gaussian mixture model. The variable blocks are formed by early-stop-and-sorted-depth-first-search (ESS-DFS) on a dendrogram created based on the mutual information between any pair of variables. Then, the variable selection is conducted by an independence test between the latent states and semi-clusters which are the smaller clusters that will be further grouped into final clusters. This package will be merged with <samp>HDclust</samp> in CRAN in the near future.</p>
</div>
<div id="variable-block-construction-by-ess-dfs" class="section level2">
<h2>2. Variable block construction by ESS-DFS</h2>
<p>Here, we illustrate the usage of HDclustVS for variable selection for high dimensional clustering based on a simulated toy example which has 300 samples, 100 relevant variables, 100 irrelevant variables and 5 clusters. genData2( ) generates the data set.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(HDclustVS)</span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(mclust)</span>
<span id="cb1-3"><a href="#cb1-3"></a><span class="co"># Data generation</span></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><a href="#cb1-4"></a><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-5"><a href="#cb1-5"></a>dat =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">genData2</span>(<span class="dt">n=</span><span class="dv">300</span>,<span class="dt">p1=</span><span class="dv">100</span>,<span class="dt">p2=</span><span class="dv">100</span>,<span class="dt">C=</span><span class="dv">5</span>,<span class="dt">rep=</span><span class="dv">1</span>) </span>
<span id="cb1-6"><a href="#cb1-6"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb1-7"><a href="#cb1-7"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb1-8"><a href="#cb1-8"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb1-9"><a href="#cb1-9"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb1-10"><a href="#cb1-10"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb1-11"><a href="#cb1-11"></a>X =<span class="st"> </span>dat[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]<span class="op">$</span>X_total</span>
<span id="cb1-12"><a href="#cb1-12"></a>Y =<span class="st"> </span>dat[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]<span class="op">$</span>z</span>
<span id="cb1-13"><a href="#cb1-13"></a>  </span>
<span id="cb1-14"><a href="#cb1-14"></a>n =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">dim</span>(X)[<span class="dv">1</span>]</span>
<span id="cb1-15"><a href="#cb1-15"></a>p =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">dim</span>(X)[<span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb1-16"><a href="#cb1-16"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-17"><a href="#cb1-17"></a><span class="co"># EDA</span></span>
<span id="cb1-18"><a href="#cb1-18"></a>Xr =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">prcomp</span>(dat[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]<span class="op">$</span>X_relev)<span class="op">$</span>x[,<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb1-19"><a href="#cb1-19"></a>Xi =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">prcomp</span>(dat[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]<span class="op">$</span>X_irrel)<span class="op">$</span>x[,<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb1-20"><a href="#cb1-20"></a>Xt =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">prcomp</span>(dat[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]<span class="op">$</span>X_total)<span class="op">$</span>x[,<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb1-21"><a href="#cb1-21"></a><span class="kw">plotCls</span>(Xr,Y,<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="st">&quot;Relevant var.&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">no.legend=</span>T)</span>
<span id="cb1-22"><a href="#cb1-22"></a><span class="kw">plotCls</span>(Xi,Y,<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="st">&quot;Irrelevant var.&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">no.legend=</span>T)</span>
<span id="cb1-23"><a href="#cb1-23"></a><span class="kw">plotCls</span>(Xt,Y,<span class="dt">title=</span><span class="st">&quot;Total var.&quot;</span>,<span class="dt">no.legend=</span>T)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="30%" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="30%" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="30%" /></p>
<p>First, variable blocks are constructed by ESS-DFS algorithm with maximum block size <span class="math inline">\(m=10\)</span> based on mutual information between any pair of variables. As the result, the algorithm generates <span class="math inline">\(30\)</span> variable blocks.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1"></a><span class="co"># The number of clusters.</span></span>
<span id="cb2-2"><a href="#cb2-2"></a>C =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">5</span></span>
<span id="cb2-3"><a href="#cb2-3"></a><span class="co"># Maximum block size is set 5% of the total dimension.</span></span>
<span id="cb2-4"><a href="#cb2-4"></a>max.vb.size =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">10</span></span>
<span id="cb2-5"><a href="#cb2-5"></a></span>
<span id="cb2-6"><a href="#cb2-6"></a><span class="co"># Calculate Mutual Information.</span></span>
<span id="cb2-7"><a href="#cb2-7"></a>pwmi =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">pairwiseMI</span>(X)</span>
<span id="cb2-8"><a href="#cb2-8"></a><span class="co"># Variable block construction by ESS-DFS.</span></span>
<span id="cb2-9"><a href="#cb2-9"></a>vbs =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">constVB</span>(X,pwmi,max.vb.size)</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="fitting-hmm-vb-or-gmm-vb" class="section level2">
<h2>3. Fitting HMM-VB or GMM-VB</h2>
<p>HMM-VB with <span class="math inline">\(C=5\)</span> components for each block is fitted. The number of components for HMM-VB is set as the true number of clusters, which we assume known.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb3"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><a href="#cb3-1"></a><span class="co"># Fitting HMM-VB with 5 components.</span></span>
<span id="cb3-2"><a href="#cb3-2"></a>fit =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">fitHmmvb</span>(X,C,vbs)</span>
<span id="cb3-3"><a href="#cb3-3"></a><span class="co"># If we want to use GMM-VB we can use fit = fitGmmvb(X,C,vbs) instead.</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="variable-block-selection-by-an-independence-test-between-semi-clusters-and-latent-states-of-variable-blocks." class="section level2">
<h2>4. Variable block selection by an independence test between semi-clusters and latent states of variable blocks.</h2>
<p>Semi-clusters are computed by dendrogram clustering of the estimated MAP state sequences based on  type of distance measure. Then, to select variable blocks, a bimodality test is applied on the normalized mutual information (NMI) between the latent states of each variable block and semi-cluster labels.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb4"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1"><a href="#cb4-1"></a><span class="co"># Semi-clusters</span></span>
<span id="cb4-2"><a href="#cb4-2"></a>semi.cls =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">semicls</span>(X,fit)</span>
<span id="cb4-3"><a href="#cb4-3"></a><span class="co"># Variable block selection by a bimodality test.</span></span>
<span id="cb4-4"><a href="#cb4-4"></a>chosen.vb =<span class="st"> </span>semi.cls<span class="op">$</span>chosen.vb</span>
<span id="cb4-5"><a href="#cb4-5"></a></span>
<span id="cb4-6"><a href="#cb4-6"></a><span class="co"># Reduce the model structure</span></span>
<span id="cb4-7"><a href="#cb4-7"></a>red.dat =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">reduceVB</span>(X,fit,chosen.vb)</span>
<span id="cb4-8"><a href="#cb4-8"></a>red.X =<span class="st"> </span>red.dat<span class="op">$</span>X</span>
<span id="cb4-9"><a href="#cb4-9"></a>red.vbs =<span class="st"> </span>red.dat<span class="op">$</span>vbs</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="retraining-of-hmm-vb-with-the-dimension-reduced-data-and-finding-final-clusters." class="section level2">
<h2>5. Retraining of HMM-VB with the dimension-reduced data and finding final clusters.</h2>
<p>Now, HMM-VB with reduced variable blocks is applied and the final clusters are computed by dendrogram clustering of the re-estimated MAP state sequences with the desired number of clusters.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb5"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb5-1"><a href="#cb5-1"></a><span class="co"># Re-estimation of the HMM-VB model with reduced dimensions</span></span>
<span id="cb5-2"><a href="#cb5-2"></a>re.fit =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">fitHmmvb</span>(red.X,C,red.vbs)</span>
<span id="cb5-3"><a href="#cb5-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb5-4"><a href="#cb5-4"></a><span class="co"># Final clustering</span></span>
<span id="cb5-5"><a href="#cb5-5"></a>final.cls =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">finalcls</span>(red.dat<span class="op">$</span>X,re.fit,C,<span class="dv">5</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>For this simulated dataset, the clustering result of HMM-VB-VS has high clustering accuracy which is measured by adjusted Rand index (ARI) and Wasserstein distance (WD) as well as perfect variable selection accuracy which is measured by F-score.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(mclust)</span>
<span id="cb6-2"><a href="#cb6-2"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(OTclust)</span>
<span id="cb6-3"><a href="#cb6-3"></a><span class="co"># The clustering and variable selection accuracy.</span></span>
<span id="cb6-4"><a href="#cb6-4"></a>ARI =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">adjustedRandIndex</span>(Y,final.cls)</span>
<span id="cb6-5"><a href="#cb6-5"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(ARI)</span>
<span id="cb6-6"><a href="#cb6-6"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.9506484</span></span>
<span id="cb6-7"><a href="#cb6-7"></a></span>
<span id="cb6-8"><a href="#cb6-8"></a>WD =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">wassDist</span>(Y,final.cls)</span>
<span id="cb6-9"><a href="#cb6-9"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(WD)</span>
<span id="cb6-10"><a href="#cb6-10"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.06529856</span></span>
<span id="cb6-11"><a href="#cb6-11"></a></span>
<span id="cb6-12"><a href="#cb6-12"></a>DRR =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">-</span><span class="kw">dim</span>(red.X)[<span class="dv">2</span>]<span class="op">/</span><span class="kw">dim</span>(X)[<span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb6-13"><a href="#cb6-13"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(DRR)</span>
<span id="cb6-14"><a href="#cb6-14"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.5</span></span>
<span id="cb6-15"><a href="#cb6-15"></a></span>
<span id="cb6-16"><a href="#cb6-16"></a>chosen.v =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">unlist</span>(fit<span class="op">$</span>vbs<span class="op">$</span>vb[chosen.vb])</span>
<span id="cb6-17"><a href="#cb6-17"></a>tp =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>(chosen.v<span class="op">&lt;=</span><span class="dv">100</span>)</span>
<span id="cb6-18"><a href="#cb6-18"></a>fp =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>(chosen.v<span class="op">&gt;</span><span class="dv">100</span>)</span>
<span id="cb6-19"><a href="#cb6-19"></a>tn =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>((<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span>p)[<span class="op">-</span>chosen.v]<span class="op">&gt;</span><span class="dv">100</span>)</span>
<span id="cb6-20"><a href="#cb6-20"></a>fn =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum</span>((<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span>p)[<span class="op">-</span>chosen.v]<span class="op">&lt;=</span><span class="dv">100</span>)</span>
<span id="cb6-21"><a href="#cb6-21"></a>  </span>
<span id="cb6-22"><a href="#cb6-22"></a>precision =<span class="st"> </span>tp<span class="op">/</span>(tp<span class="op">+</span>fp)</span>
<span id="cb6-23"><a href="#cb6-23"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(precision)</span>
<span id="cb6-24"><a href="#cb6-24"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 1</span></span>
<span id="cb6-25"><a href="#cb6-25"></a></span>
<span id="cb6-26"><a href="#cb6-26"></a>recall =<span class="st"> </span>tp<span class="op">/</span>(tp<span class="op">+</span>fn)</span>
<span id="cb6-27"><a href="#cb6-27"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(recall)</span>
<span id="cb6-28"><a href="#cb6-28"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 1</span></span>
<span id="cb6-29"><a href="#cb6-29"></a></span>
<span id="cb6-30"><a href="#cb6-30"></a>F1 =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">2</span><span class="op">/</span>(<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">/</span>precision<span class="op">+</span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">/</span>recall)</span>
<span id="cb6-31"><a href="#cb6-31"></a><span class="kw">print</span>(F1)</span>
<span id="cb6-32"><a href="#cb6-32"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 1</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
